{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21891"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21891"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.04,0.03,0.01,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108290"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14801"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21891"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90691"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"38038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38039"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108290"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever, confusion, and shortness of breath. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her regular medications are metformin and perindopril. She does not smoke or drink alcohol. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 92/56 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 38.6\u00b0C. She is drowsy but rousable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA quick Sequential Organ Failure Assessment (qSOFA) was performed, which incorporates the following criteria (one point for each): \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ealtered mental status\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esystolic blood pressure \u2264100 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eand respiratory rate \u226522/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the correct interpretation of the qSOFA score in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["She meets diagnostic criteria for sepsis","She requires immediate intubation","She has a low risk of in-hospital mortality","She does not require further monitoring","She is at increased risk of poor outcome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe meets diagnostic criteria for sepsis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While a high qSOFA score suggests increased risk, it does not itself diagnose sepsis. Sepsis is defined as life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by a dysregulated host response to infection, typically using the full Sequential Organ Failure Assessment (SOFA) score or clinical judgement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe requires immediate intubation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The qSOFA score does not determine the need for intubation. Airway management decisions are based on clinical assessment of respiratory failure, airway protection, and other factors, not the qSOFA score alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe has a low risk of in-hospital mortality\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. A qSOFA score of three indicates a high risk of poor outcome, not a low risk. Studies show that patients with qSOFA scores of 2 or more have significantly higher mortality rates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe does not require further monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. A high qSOFA score should prompt increased monitoring and consideration of intensive care, not less monitoring. These patients require close observation for signs of deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShe is at increased risk of poor outcome\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. A quick Sequential Organ Failure Assessment (qSOFA) score of 2 or more (in this case, three: altered mental status, systolic blood pressure \u2264100 mmHg, and respiratory rate \u226522/min) identifies patients with suspected infection who are at higher risk of in-hospital mortality and prolonged intensive care unit stay. This should prompt urgent assessment, escalation of care, and close monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe qSOFA score is a rapid bedside tool to help identify patients with suspected infection who are at increased risk of deterioration, but it does not replace clinical judgement or the need for comprehensive assessment and management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The quick Sequential Organ Failure Assessment (qSOFA) score uses three criteria: altered mental status, systolic blood pressure \u2264100 mmHg, and respiratory rate \u226522/min.","A qSOFA score of 2 or more identifies patients with suspected infection at increased risk of poor outcomes and prompts escalation of care.","qSOFA is a screening tool for risk stratification, not a diagnostic tool for sepsis, which requires evidence of organ dysfunction due to infection."],"references":["Kashyap R, Sherani KM, Dutt T, Gnanapandithan K, Sagar M, Vallabhajosyula S, Vakil AP, Surani S. Current Utility of Sequential Organ Failure Assessment Score: A Literature Review and Future Directions. Open Respir Med J. 2021 Apr 13;15:1-6. doi: 10.2174/1874306402115010001. PMID: 34249175; PMCID: PMC8227444. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34249175/","Moreno R, Rhodes A, Piquilloud L, Hernandez G, Takala J, Gershengorn HB, Tavares M, Coopersmith CM, Myatra SN, Singer M, Rezende E, Prescott HC, Soares M, Timsit JF, de Lange DW, Jung C, De Waele JJ, Martin GS, Summers C, Azoulay E, Fujii T, McLean AS, Vincent JL. The Sequential Organ Failure Assessment (SOFA) Score: has the time come for an update? Crit Care. 2023 Jan 13;27(1):15. doi: 10.1186/s13054-022-04290-9. PMID: 36639780; PMCID: PMC9837980. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36639780/","Marmiere M, D\u0027Amico F, Monti G, Landoni G. Mastering the Sequential Organ Failure Assessment Score: Critical Choices of Score Statistic, Timing, Imputations, and Competing Risk Handling in Major Trials-A Systematic Review. Crit Care Med. 2025 May 1;53(5):e1116-e1124. doi: 10.1097/CCM.0000000000006532. Epub 2024 Dec 4. PMID: 39631051. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39631051/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90691"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21891"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90691"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-09T11:30:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-09T11:31:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14801"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108290"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://a